    <text id="F8507T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Cook's letter to McPherson alludes to a difference in their respective political
                    opinions and encourages McPherson to stay "true to the Union."</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
         

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1860-12-20"><abbr expan="December">Dec</abbr> 20 1860</date>
                        <name type="place">Chambersburg, <abbr expan="Pennsylvania">Pa.</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute><abbr expan="Honorable">Hon</abbr>
                        <abbr expan="Edward">Ed<hi rend="super">d</hi></abbr> McPherson,<lb/>My Dear
                        Sir,</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>In the crisis now upon us be true to the Union.</p>

                <p>You are aware of my position politically; but in my esteem you were second, in
                    the late contest, to no man in your party.</p>

                <p>Our Union was gained at immense sacrifice, and should not be cast to the winds as
                    a bubble. Do not permit personal aspirations or friendships to control you; but
                    give your whole energies for your country united and indivisible.</p>

                <p>Any documents to my address under your frank would be regarded by me as evidences
                    of Friendship in the past and continued.</p>

                <p>Keep me in remembrance as a personal friend and believe me</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Your <abbr expan="Obedient">Obt</abbr> Servant</salute>
                    <signed>W. I. Cook</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
